1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:05,226
Cross-case analysis is useful when your question depends on comparison.

2
00:00:05,226 --> 00:00:10,372
In QualCanvas, a case can represent a participant, site, organisation

3
00:00:10,372 --> 00:00:13,974
or another unit that your method defines.

4
00:00:13,974 --> 00:00:17,576
Decide that unit before building the comparison.

5
00:00:17,976 --> 00:00:20,424
Open Tools and choose Cases.

6
00:00:20,424 --> 00:00:25,320
Give each case a safe research label and a short

7
00:00:25,320 --> 00:00:28,258
description that explains what it represents.

8
00:00:28,258 --> 00:00:32,664
Avoid putting identifiable participant details into the display name.

9
00:00:33,064 --> 00:00:37,624
Link the relevant transcripts or imported responses to each case.

10
00:00:37,624 --> 00:00:42,184
Check the assignments carefully: a missing or duplicated source can

11
00:00:42,184 --> 00:00:46,288
produce a convincing-looking comparison based on the wrong membership.

12
00:00:46,688 --> 00:00:49,448
Choose Cross-Case from the Tools menu.

13
00:00:49,448 --> 00:00:54,048
QualCanvas summarises how codes appear across the cases you created.

14
00:00:54,048 --> 00:00:58,648
Treat the view as a route back to evidence, not

15
00:00:58,648 --> 00:01:00,488
as an automatic conclusion.

16
00:01:00,888 --> 00:01:06,413
For a structured case-by-question view, open Analyze and choose Framework Matrix.

17
00:01:06,413 --> 00:01:11,436
The matrix supports systematic comparison while preserving the need to

18
00:01:11,436 --> 00:01:14,952
inspect the original excerpts and contextual notes.

19
00:01:15,352 --> 00:01:19,463
Write down why a difference may matter, what context could

20
00:01:19,463 --> 00:01:23,574
explain it and which case does not fit the emerging

21
00:01:23,574 --> 00:01:23,985
account.

22
00:01:23,985 --> 00:01:28,096
A comparison becomes analytically useful when its reasoning is documented.

23
00:01:28,496 --> 00:01:33,042
Define the unit, assign sources consistently, compare patterns, return to

24
00:01:33,042 --> 00:01:35,769
the evidence and memo your reasoning.

25
00:01:35,769 --> 00:01:40,315
Continue in the training centre with the QDPX transfer tutorial

26
00:01:40,315 --> 00:01:43,952
when a project needs to move between tools.
